snippet.textDisplay: Ok. What he doesn’t mention is there are different kinds of henna. Different varieties are grown in different countries. Depending on what kind you use the kind of red you get will vary. I have used brewed coffee and tea in my henna mix because the dark brown helps to tone down the red (I didn’t want Ronald McDonald hair) not because it was necessary to activate the henna. By doing this the henna is only visible on my grays and looks like I have highlights while the rest maintains my natural color which I love. I am not someone willing to put permanent color or bleach in my hair because it’s too damaging. Also henna is used as a conditioning treatment. I and other people sometimes use henna or Cassia (neutral henna)  doesn’t deposit color. Some people I know are allergic to traditional hair dye because of a chemical in it. Their faces blow up like balloons.

snippet.textDisplay: I've went from black to blonde in 24 hours. 30 volume and 2 oz white no blue/filler bleach. That process 4 times 40 mins each with a wash and oil in between air-dry each time. Then one more time with that process for 25 minutes,  toner and then always have a natural oil like grapeseed oil and a thickener oil like smooth'nshine for UV protection for the raw oil I put on my hair first. My normal hair is wavy, thick, and medium coarse.

Then one more time with that process for 25 minutes,  toner and then always have a natural oil like grapeseed oil and a thickener oil like smooth'nshine for UV protection for the raw oil I put on my hair first. My normal hair is wavy, thick, and medium coarse.
